353–1411":"1353–1411","1354–Female":"1354–Deceased","1360–1420":"1360–1420","1377–1449":"1377–1449","1380–Male":"1380–Deceased","1383–Male":"1383–Deceased","1323–1410":"1323–1410","1325–Female":"1325–Deceased","1383":"1383","1360":"1360","1380":"1380","1325":"1325","1411":"1411","1323":"1323","1377":"1377","1410":"1410","1420":"1420","1354":"1354","1353":"1353","about 1376":"about 1376","1449":"1449","Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Findon, Aberdeenshire, Scotland":"Findon, Aberdeenshire, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland, United Kingdom","Castle Menzies, Weem, Aberfeldy, Perth, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Weem, Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Castle Menzies, Weem, Aberfeldy, Perth, Scotland":"Weem, Perthshire, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Menzies","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Manners  , in which the <i>z</i> was originally the Middle English letter <i>ʒ</i> (yogh), representing a sound similar to modern English <i>y</i>. The surname is pronounced <i>Meenyus</i> or <i>Minyas</i> in Scotland. The name was brought to Scotland in the 12th or 13th century by a family of Norman knights. It appears that the name was re-interpreted in Gaelic as containing a personal name, and for variants ending <i>-s</i> there is a possibility of confusion with   McManus  . See also   McMinn  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Minges","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Gunter, Kurt.","Altered form of Scottish   Menzies  , reflecting the traditional Scottish pronunciation of that name.","German: variant of   Menges   1 or 2."]},{"name":"Mingus","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Menzies  , which is traditionallypronounced ‘mingiz’."]},{"name":"Manners","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): habitational name from Mesnières-en-Bray in Seine-Maritime, recorded in the 13th century as <i>Maneria</i>, a derivative of Latin <i>manere</i> ‘to remain, abide, reside’. See also   Menzies  ."]},{"name":"Menzie","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Menzies  ."]},{"name":"McMinn","meanings":["Scottish and northern Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Méinn</b> ‘son of <i>Méinn</i>’, a Gaelic interpretation of   Menzies   as a relationship surname."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Chief Sir Robert de Menzies was born in 1353, in Weem, Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom, his father, John De Menzies 4th Menzies Clan Chief, was 30 and his mother, Mrs John Menzies, was 29. He married Jean Atholia about 1376, in Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. He died in 1411, in his hometown, at the age of 58."},"et":{"1353–1411":"1353–1411","1354–Female":"1354–Surnud","1360–1420":"1360–1420","1377–1449":"1377–1449","1380–Male":"1380–Surnud","1383–Male":"1383–Surnud","1323–1410":"1323–1410","1325–Female":"1325–Surnud","1383":"1383","1360":"1360","1380":"1380","1325":"1325","1411":"1411","1323":"1323","1377":"1377","1410":"1410","1420":"1420","1354":"1354","1353":"1353","about 1376":"umbes 1376","1449":"1449","Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Perthshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Findon, Aberdeenshire, Scotland":"Findon, Aberdeenshire, Scotland","Scotland":"Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Castle Menzies, Weem, Aberfeldy, Perth, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Weem, Perthshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Castle Menzies, Weem, Aberfeldy, Perth, Scotland":"Weem, Perthshire, Scotland"},"fi":{"1353–1411":"1353–1411","1354–Female":"1354–Kuollut","1360–1420":"1360–1420","1377–1449":"1377–1449","1380–Male":"1380–Kuollut","1383–Male":"1383–Kuollut","1323–1410":"1323–1410","1325–Female":"1325–Kuollut","1383":"1383","1360":"1360","1380":"1380","1325":"1325","1411":"1411","1323":"1323","1377":"1377","1410":"1410","1420":"1420","1354":"1354","1353":"1353","about 1376":"noin 1376","1449":"1449","Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Perthshire, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Findon, Aberdeenshire, Scotland":"Findon, Aberdeenshire, Scotland","Scotland":"Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Castle Menzies, Weem, Aberfeldy, Perth, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Weem, Perthshire, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Castle Menzies, Weem, Aberfeldy, Perth, Scotland":"Weem, Perthshire, Scotland"}